  'Meeting Notes: Tristan Pelligrino and Kyley Crews',
  '## **Content Development and Copywriting Strategy**

The team agreed to prioritize finalizing the **homepage** and **platform pages** by the end of this month to align content development with design and build schedules (05:18).  
- **Kyley Crews** emphasized starting with the homepage to establish alignment before moving through the sitemap sequentially, focusing on platform content first as it’s the most urgent.  
- **Jenny Vance** proposed dedicating a full day offline for Kyley to concentrate on platform content next week, minimizing distractions from Slack and other communications, to speed the drafting process.  
- The strategy involves iterative internal reviews and just-in-time content delivery to keep momentum while allowing flexibility for refinement.  
- This focused content sprint approach aims to deliver platform pages as a batch, enabling smooth transition into solution and industry pages by targeting completion around the **25th of the month**.

The team plans to leverage AI tools like **Twain** for customizing industry pages based on a single well-written template, reducing workload for repetitive content while maintaining tone consistency (08:54).  
- This reuse strategy was suggested to mitigate the daunting volume of industry-specific pages and speed up production.  
- Collaboration with the KG team will help integrate AI prompts for effective content generation, streamlining writing and editing efforts.  
- This approach supports scalability and faster delivery without compromising content quality or voice.

## **Design and User Experience Planning**

The group confirmed a process to pair wireframes with corresponding copy drafts to ensure design and content flow naturally together before development begins (02:01).  
- Each sitemap page includes low-fidelity wireframe blocks with guidelines on content length, purpose, and visual elements to inform copywriting.  
- The plan is to receive a **Figma design mockup** of the homepage after copy approval, providing a visual checkpoint before building starts (17:01).  
- This step will allow stakeholders to review integrated copy and design, ensuring components like navigation and footer are reusable across pages.  
- Early parallel development of reusable components will accelerate build timelines once content is finalized.

The team is working on sourcing authentic, branded photography to enhance the site’s visual appeal and reflect company culture (18:05).  
- A photo contest yielded a large volume of employee-submitted pictures, supplemented by professional headshots and nature shots to reinforce the brand’s natural, human feel.  
- **Jenny Vance** highlighted the need for explicit permission when using images featuring faces, maintaining legal and ethical standards.  
- Organic, candid images such as the “Power Rangers” team group shot are prioritized for their genuine cultural resonance.  
- These assets will be curated and edited to balance quality with authenticity, supporting the site’s storytelling approach.

## **Project Timelines and Collaboration Cadence**

The team agreed to weekly check-ins on **Fridays at 12:30 PM**, starting the **14th**, to monitor progress and adjust plans as needed (29:55).  
- Kyley’s morning schedule is busy, so Friday afternoons were chosen for consistent, manageable status updates.  
- Deliverables such as the homepage copy draft are expected this week, with design feedback and iteration scheduled for early next week (29:20).  
- The cadence supports rapid turnaround while accommodating individual workloads and external dependencies.

Collaboration will include close coordination with internal experts like **Jenny B.** for technical platform details and **Brianna** for design elements such as screen grab styles (11:15, 13:39).  
- Jenny B. is tasked to provide high-level bullet points for the platform features by early next week to inform content creation.  
- Brianna is handling decisions on visual presentation preferences (e.g., monitor displays vs. isolated images) to balance aesthetics and usability.  
- This cross-functional cooperation is designed to reduce bottlenecks and ensure content accuracy and design consistency.

## **Scope and Budget Alignment on Design Assets**

The team clarified the budget and scope for redesigning key resources like **Tier 2 guide** and **Brickwork guide**, agreeing on a design cost of approximately **$3,500** for both combined, not per guide, which is roughly half of earlier misestimated figures (23:38).  
- This budget includes adapting existing content into new designs rather than full rewrites, optimizing cost-efficiency.  
- The guides will be designed primarily in **InDesign**, with options to create **Canva templates** for internal reuse and easy updates by marketing teams (26:25).  
- Designing reusable templates for documents, landing pages, and social media posts is under consideration to support ongoing content needs.  
- The team also discussed the possibility of engaging external designers billed at **$90 per hour**, providing flexibility for additional workload without doubling internal costs.

Non-website assets such as offsite **ebooks, videos, and checklists** fall outside the current scope for redesign but may be revisited later based on business priorities (21:26).  
- Case study pages and blog posts will be reformatted within the new website design template, ensuring brand consistency while keeping content intact.  
- Decisions on how to handle existing video content and resource-heavy items will be made in future planning discussions.  
- This delineation helps manage workload and budget by focusing immediate efforts on core website content and design.

## **Strategic Vision and Market Positioning**

The team presented the website redesign as a subtle but important update aimed at better reflecting the company’s brand soul and improving user engagement without a major PR push (15:05).  
- **Jenny Vance** shared that leadership and stakeholders responded positively to early design concepts, showing excitement about the refreshed look and feel.  
- The target launch date is set for **December 15th**, with a fallback to year-end if needed, balancing quality with timely delivery.  
- This update addresses current issues where content and design lack alignment, especially on product and solution pages, improving clarity and brand cohesion.  
- The goal is to increase meaningful visitor engagement rather than focusing on volume or broad marketing blitzes.

The redesign supports longer-term business goals by creating a scalable framework for content and design that can adapt as new products and solutions evolve (16:39).  
- The integration of AI-assisted content generation and reusable design templates is part of a strategic push to improve efficiency and maintain brand voice.  
- The approach also anticipates future needs for modular content updates, enabling faster response to market changes or customer feedback.  
- This positions the company competitively by enhancing digital presence without overextending resources.

## **Process Improvements and Operational Enhancements**

The team emphasized process discipline around “heads down” days for content creation to maximize efficiency and minimize context switching (12:20).  
- Jenny recommended strict offline periods with Slack and email turned off, allowing focused work punctuated by brief check-ins as needed.  
- This method showed prior success in accelerating draft completion and is planned to continue for upcoming platform content sprints.  
- The approach reflects a shift toward more deliberate work cycles to improve quality and speed, reducing iterative back-and-forth delays.

Quality assurance will include early internal reviews with technical experts to validate content accuracy before wider circulation (25:20).  
- Kyley is coordinating with technical team members, including one in Japan with a different timezone, to finalize copy this week.  
- This early vetting minimizes rework during design and development phases, keeping the project on track.  
- The team also plans to use shared Google Docs with embedded notes to streamline collaboration and feedback incorporation.

The workflow from content to design to build will be tightly integrated, with each major section receiving a design iteration before moving to development (29:20).  
- This phased handoff allows for clear approvals and reduces risks of misalignment between content and visual design.  
- Developers will start building reusable components like navigation and footers based on early design approvals, enabling parallel progress.  
- This operational setup aims to shorten overall project timelines while maintaining high quality and cross-team visibility.',
